- Since reading of any sort is an activity, all reading must to some degree be active.
- On the contrary, the reader or listener is much more like the catcher in a game of baseball.
- The art of reading is the skill of catching every sort of communication as well as possible.
- You gradually lift yourself from _a state of understanding less to one of understanding more._
- The mind passes from understanding less to understanding more. The skilled operations that cause this to happen are the various acts that constitute the art of reading
- Here the thing to be read is initially better or higher than the reader.
- Here by “learning” is meant understanding more, not remembering more information
- We do not want to give the impression that facts, leading to increased information, and insights, leading to increased understanding, are always easy to distinguish.
- This book is about the art of reading for the sake of increased understanding.
#### The Difference Between Learning by Instruction and Learning by Discovery
- To be [[enlightened]] [[Baron de Montesquieu (1689–1755)]] is to know, in addition, what it is all about: why it is the case, what its connections are with other facts, in what respects it is the same, in what respects it is different, and so forth.
-  Being informed is prerequisite to being enlightened.
- The Greeks had a name for such a mixture of learning and folly which might be applied to the bookish but poorly read of all ages. They are all _sophomores._
- There must be discovery—the process of learning something by research, by investigation, or by reflection, without being taught.
- Thinking is only one part of the activity of learning. One must also use one’s senses and imagination.
